The linear curriculum model prescribes a logical, step-by-step approach for curriculum creation that begins with goals and progresses from there. The linear curriculum models are comprised of the following types of models:  First, it has been proposed by Tyler Rationale Linear Model(1949) that a sequential pattern for curriculum development be followed. This pattern starts with goal setting, moves on to learning experiences, the organization of learning experiences, and the assessment of learning experiences, and ends with the evaluation of learning experiences.  Second, a modified version of the Tyler Rationale Model is Taba's Grassroots Rationale Model (developed by Hilda Taba in 1962). She stated that curriculum creation should be carried out in a linear and logical manner, and she advocated for more information input throughout the process. She said that all curricula are formed of core aspects and that they may be made effective if the requirements of the students are identified. Taba pointed out that the nature of the goals dictates the kind of learning that would take place.  Third, Allan Glatthorn established a Standard-based Curriculum Model, which was meant to be used for curricular standards in any field, ranging from basic education to higher education.  Fourth, the Understanding by Design Model (UbD) (Wiggins and McTighe, 2002) is often known as backward design since it emphasizes the need of beginning with goals and objectives while developing instructional materials. It placed a strong focus on developing curriculum that encourages students to explore and improve their grasp of significant concepts, as well as on the design of examinations.  Fifth, the Systematic Design Model (Robert Diamond, 1960) has seen several significant alterations since its inception in 1998, but its basic structure has not altered. Include two fundamental phases: (1) the selection and design of the project, and (2) the production, execution, and assessment of the project. Diamond argued that, in an ideal situation, certain activities must come before others, and some choices should not be taken until all relevant data have been. gathered and considered together.  Lastly, sequential and logical method to curriculum creation is prescribed by the Murray Print Model Curriculum Design (Murray Print, 1988), which provides a practical and simple to comprehend procedure for building curriculum.
